Option 2: Disable Via Database (Direct Command)
If the setting persists or you prefer a command-line approach, you can update the database setting directly, similar to how you modified the captcha setting earlier.

bash
# Enter the container first
docker exec -it jms_core bash

# Navigate to the app directory and open Django shell
cd /opt/jumpserver/apps
python manage.py shell
At the Python prompt, run:

python
from settings.models import Setting
from django.core.cache import cache

# Disable the watermark
Setting.objects.update_or_create(
    name='SECURITY_WATERMARK_ENABLED',
    defaults={'value': 'false', 'category': 'security'}
)
print("Watermark disabled.")

# Clear cache to apply immediately
cache.clear()
print("Cache cleared.")
exit()
After updating the database, restart the container for good measure:

bash
exit
docker restart jms_core